[[File:Macuiltonaleque 1.jpg|thumb|Macuiltonaleque, Códice Borgia.]]
'''Ahuiateteo'''{{Pronunciation-needed}} or '''Macuiltonaleque'''{{Pronunciation-needed}} were a group of five [[Aztec mythology|Aztec gods]] of [[wikt:excess|excess]] and [[pleasure]]. They also represented the dangers that come along with these. These five gods were also invoked by [[diviner]]s and [[Mysticism|mystics]].<ref name="MillerTaube93,03,p40">Miller and Taube 1993, 2003, p. 40.</ref> They were associated with the [[Tzitzimitl|Tzitzimimeh]], a group of frightening beings that personified death, drought, and war.<ref>Pohl 1998, pp. 194–195.</ref>

The five gods are:<ref name="MillerTaube93,03,p40"/>
* Macuilcozcacuauhtli{{Pronunciation-needed}} (Five [[vulture]]), the god of [[gluttony]]
* Macuilcuetzpalin{{Pronunciation-needed}} (Five [[lizard]])
* Macuilmalinalli{{Pronunciation-needed}} (Five [[grass]])
* [[Macuiltochtli]]{{Pronunciation-needed}} (Five [[rabbit]]), the god of [[drunkenness]]
* Macuilxochitl{{Pronunciation-needed}} (Five [[flower]]), the god of [[gambling]] and [[music]], and an aspect of [[Xochipili]]

